# Next.js 16 Conventions

## Version-specific rules (Next 16, not 14/15)

- `params` and `searchParams` in pages, layouts, and route handlers are **always
  a `Promise`** — always `await props.params` / `await props.searchParams`.
  Never write a signature that treats them as plain objects.
  ```typescript
  export default async function Page(props: PageProps<'/deals/[slug]'>) {
    const { slug } = await props.params;
    const query = await props.searchParams;
    // ...
  }
  ```
- If auth/header logic is ever needed on requests (unlikely for this project,
  but noting it), it goes in `proxy.ts` at the project root, not `middleware.ts`
  — the file was renamed and runs on the Node.js runtime only, not Edge.
- Don't assume a page is statically cached by default — Next 16's default is
  request-time/dynamic. If a deals listing page should be cached between
  ingestion runs, cache it explicitly (`use cache` directive on the fetch/query
  function) rather than relying on implicit static generation.
- Turbopack is the default bundler — no webpack config needed unless something
  specific breaks under it.

- Server Components by default for anything reading deal data. Client Components
  only for interactive filter/sort controls — keep them thin, push state to the
  URL (searchParams) rather than local-only state so filtered views are shareable
  and linkable.
- Ingestion jobs live under `src/app/api/cron/<source>/route.ts`, one route per
  source, each calling that source's `fetchDeals()` + upsert independently.
  Protect these with a shared secret header check (`CRON_SECRET`), not just
  relying on the platform's cron auth.
- Every cron route calls `recordSourceRun()` (`040-database.mdc`) exactly once
  per invocation, in both the success and failure paths — wrap the fetch+upsert
  in try/catch and record the outcome either way. This is what powers `/status`
  (`070-implementation-plan.mdc`); a cron route that doesn't call it is a bug.
- No source's cron route imports another source's module — isolation from
  `030-scrapers.mdc` applies here too; one route timing out or 500ing must not
  affect the others.
- Data fetching for pages goes through the DB query layer (`src/lib/db`), never
  a direct call to CheapShark/ITAD/scrapers from a page or route handler outside
  the cron jobs.
- Use `revalidatePath`/`revalidateTag` after a successful ingestion run instead of
  time-based ISR guessing, so the site updates right after a refresh completes
  rather than on a fixed timer.
